    All induction, including the examples given so far, arises from some change in magnetic flux  *Φ size 12&#123;Φ&#125; &#123;&#125;*. For example, Faraday changed  *B size 12&#123;B&#125; &#123;&#125;* and hence  *Φ size 12&#123;Φ&#125; &#123;&#125;* when opening and closing the switch in his apparatus (shown in {'Figure_24_1_1 Figure 24.1.1}). This is also true for the bar magnet and coil shown in {'Figure_24_1_2 Figure 24.1.2}. When rotating the coil of a generator, the angle <math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" xmlns:md="http://cnx.rice.edu/mdml" xmlns="http://cnx.rice.edu/cnxml"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi>θ</mi></mrow><mrow/></mrow><annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12&#123;θ&#125; &#123;&#125;</annotation></semantics></math> and, hence,  *Φ size 12&#123;Φ&#125; &#123;&#125;* is changed. Just how great an emf and what direction it takes depend on the change in  *Φ size 12&#123;Φ&#125; &#123;&#125;* and how rapidly the change is made, as examined in the next section.

